{"id": "20176", "post": "<div class=\"post-20176 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-virtual-servers category-tutorials tag-apache tag-epel tag-lamp tag-lets-encrypt tag-linux tag-mariadb tag-mysql tag-php tag-php-7-3 tag-php-fpm tag-redis tag-ssl tag-virtual-hosting\" id=\"post-20176\"><h2 class=\"storytitle\"><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/blog/centos-7-lamp-server-tutorial-part-5-speeding-up-wordpress-with-redis/\" rel=\"bookmark\">CentOS 7 LAMP Server Tutorial Part 5: Speeding up WordPress with Redis</a></h2><div class=\"meta\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"/media/icons/tag_green.png\" data-src=\"/media/icons/tag_green.png\" alt=\"Tags: \" class=\"litespeed-loaded\" data-was-processed=\"true\"> <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/apache/\" rel=\"tag\">apache</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/epel/\" rel=\"tag\">epel</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/lamp/\" rel=\"tag\">LAMP</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/lets-encrypt/\" rel=\"tag\">Let's Encrypt</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/linux/\" rel=\"tag\">linux</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/mariadb/\" rel=\"tag\">mariadb</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/mysql/\" rel=\"tag\">mysql</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/php/\" rel=\"tag\">PHP</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/php-7-3/\" rel=\"tag\">php 7.3</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/php-fpm/\" rel=\"tag\">PHP-FPM</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/redis/\" rel=\"tag\">redis</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/ssl/\" rel=\"tag\">ssl</a>, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/tag/virtual-hosting/\" rel=\"tag\">virtual hosting</a> <img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"https://lowendbox.com/media/icons/calendar.png\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/media/icons/calendar.png\" alt=\"Date/Time: \" class=\"litespeed-loaded\" data-was-processed=\"true\"> July 1, 2019 @ 7:10 am, by Ryan Flowers</div><div class=\"storycontent tablelook\"><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In the <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/blog/centos-7-lamp-server-tutorial-modernized-and-explained-part-1/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">previous CentOS 7 LAMP Server Tutorials</a>, we configured a LAMP stack, <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/blog/centos-7-lamp-server-tutorial-part-3-lets-encrypt-ssl/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">secured it with Let\u2019s Encrypt SSL certificates</a>, and <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/blog/centos-7-lamp-server-wordpress-wp-cli/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">installed WordPress with WP-CLI</a>. Here in Part 5 we\u2019re going to up our game just a bit more by installing server side caching with a program called Redis. Then we\u2019ll configure WordPress to use Redis and check our performance to see if Redis actually made an impact. Let\u2019s get started!</span></p><p><span id=\"more-20176\"></span></p><h1><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What is Redis?</span></h1><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/redis-icon-logo.png.webp\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"wp-image-20191 alignleft litespeed-loaded\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/redis-icon-logo.png.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"103\" height=\"103\" align=\"left\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/redis-icon-logo.png.webp 280w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/redis-icon-logo-150x150.png.webp 150w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 103px) 100vw, 103px\" sizes=\"(max-width: 103px) 100vw, 103px\" srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/redis-icon-logo.png.webp 280w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/redis-icon-logo-150x150.png.webp 150w\" data-was-processed=\"true\">According to redis.io, Redis is a \u201cdata structure store\u201d which is used as an in memory database. Because it stores information (called \u201cobjects\u201d) in memory, it saves the server the trouble of having to look in its database. In this way it serves as a cache, and as such can help the server handle more traffic without having to work harder to do it.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">By default, WordPress doesn\u2019t know how to use Redis. We\u2019re going to enable WordPress to use Redis by installing a WordPress caching plugin called \u201cW3 Total Cache\u201d. First, we need to install Redis and get it started.</span></p><h1><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Installing Redis</span></h1><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Redis is available from the CentOS \u201cExtra Packages for Enterprise Linux\u201d (EPEL) software repository. If you\u2019ve followed this tutorial series from the beginning, then the CentOS EPEL repository is already enabled. If not, then you\u2019ll need to enable it now using the following command:</span></p><pre><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">yum -y install epel-release</span></pre><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now you\u2019re ready to install Redis. It\u2019s all too easy, just a quick Yum install. Run the following command:</span></p><pre><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">yum -y install redis</span></pre><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Here\u2019s how that looked on our VPS:</span></p><p><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install.png\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-1024x341.png.webp\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-20187 litespeed-loaded\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-1024x341.png.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"900\" height=\"300\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-1024x341.png.webp 1024w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-300x100.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-768x256.png.webp 768w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install.png 1053w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" sizes=\"(max-width: 900px) 100vw, 900px\" srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-1024x341.png.webp 1024w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-300x100.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-768x256.png.webp 768w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install.png 1053w\" data-was-processed=\"true\"></a></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">With Redis now installed, we need to start Redis for the first time and configure CentOS to launch Redis at startup. Run the following commands:</span></p><pre><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">systemctl start redis\n</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">systemctl enable redis</span></pre><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Here\u2019s how those commands looked on our VPS:</span></p><p><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Start.png\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Start.png\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-20185 litespeed-loaded\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Start.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"895\" height=\"60\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Start.png 1000w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Start-300x20.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Start-768x51.png.webp 768w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 895px) 100vw, 895px\" sizes=\"(max-width: 895px) 100vw, 895px\" srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Start.png 1000w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Start-300x20.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Start-768x51.png.webp 768w\" data-was-processed=\"true\"></a></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Lastly, we need to make sure that Redis is actually started and that it is reachable. Much like PHP-FPM\u2019s default configuration, Redis listens on the \u201clocalhost\u201d IP (127.0.0.1) on a specific port (6379). Other programs can communicate with Redis by making a connection to that IP and port.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">We\u2019re going to test that communication now using the redis-cli program. Just like you can ping an IP with the \u201cping\u201d command, you can also ping Redis with the \u201credis-cli ping\u201d command. If Redis is running properly, it\u2019ll simply reply with \u201cPONG\u201d. Give it a try:</span></p><pre><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">redis-cli ping</span></pre><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Ours was running properly, and here\u2019s how it looked:</span></p><p><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Pingpong.png\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSI5MDUiIGhlaWdodD0iODYiIHZpZXdCb3g9IjAgMCA5MDUgODYiPjxyZWN0IHdpZHRoPSIxMDAlIiBoZWlnaHQ9IjEwMCUiIGZpbGw9IiNjZmQ0ZGIiLz48L3N2Zz4=\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter wp-image-20188\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Pingpong.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"905\" height=\"86\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Pingpong.png 1000w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Pingpong-300x29.png.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Pingpong-768x73.png.webp 768w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 905px) 100vw, 905px\"></a></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you got \u201cPONG\u201d, then great! Redis is running and you\u2019re ready to configure WordPress to take advantage of it. Almost. First, we need to get PHP up to speed.</span></p><h1><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Enabling Redis in PHP 7.3</span></h1><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Now that we know that Redis is working, we need to give PHP the ability to talk to Redis. Thankfully, this is as simple as installing the PHP 7.3 Redis extension and restarting PHP-FPM. If you\u2019ve followed our tutorial, then the following commands will do the job:</span></p><pre><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">yum -y install php73-php-redis\n</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">systemctl restart php73-php-fpm</span></pre><h1><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Configuring WordPress to use Redis</span></h1><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">As previously mentioned, WordPress doesn\u2019t have the know-how to use Redis. It also doesn\u2019t have any built in caching. We will solve both of those problems by installing the W3 Total Cache plugin for WordPress. Log in to your WordPress Dashboard, and go to Plugins &gt; Add New. Search for \u201cW3 Total Cache\u201d and click on \u201cInstall Now\u201d as shown below:</span></p><p><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-W3TC.jpg\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSI5MTMiIGhlaWdodD0iMzg2IiB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgOTEzIDM4NiI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEwMCUiIGhlaWdodD0iMTAwJSIgZmlsbD0iI2NmZDRkYiIvPjwvc3ZnPg==\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-20181\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-W3TC.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"913\" height=\"386\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-W3TC.jpg.webp 913w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-W3TC-300x127.jpg.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Install-W3TC-768x325.jpg.webp 768w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 913px) 100vw, 913px\"></a></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Click on Activate to enable W3 Total Cache. You\u2019ll see a new menu item in the WordPress Dashboard: \u201cPerformance\u201d. Click on Performance &gt; General to get into the W3 Total Cache settings.</span></p><p><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-W3TC-General.jpg\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSIzMjIiIGhlaWdodD0iMTI2IiB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgMzIyIDEyNiI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEwMCUiIGhlaWdodD0iMTAwJSIgZmlsbD0iI2NmZDRkYiIvPjwvc3ZnPg==\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-20182\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-W3TC-General.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"322\" height=\"126\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-W3TC-General.jpg.webp 322w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-W3TC-General-300x117.jpg.webp 300w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 322px) 100vw, 322px\"></a></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Go to each cache setting and enable it, and choose \u201cRedis\u201d from the drop down if it is available. If Redis is not available on any of the dropdowns and is greyed out, then it\u2019s likely that either Redis isn\u2019t installed, running, or enabled in PHP. You\u2019ll need to retrace the previous steps taken before continuing.</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Once all of the caches are enabled and Redis is selected, click on \u201cSave All Settings\u201d as shown below:</span></p><p><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-W3TC-Settings.jpg\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSI1NjMiIGhlaWdodD0iNDQwIiB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgNTYzIDQ0MCI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEwMCUiIGhlaWdodD0iMTAwJSIgZmlsbD0iI2NmZDRkYiIvPjwvc3ZnPg==\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-20183\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-W3TC-Settings.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"563\" height=\"440\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-W3TC-Settings.jpg.webp 563w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-W3TC-Settings-300x234.jpg.webp 300w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 563px) 100vw, 563px\"></a></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Check the function of your site. If your site doesn\u2019t look correct, you may need to change the Minification settings, as those can often cause problems with CSS and Javascript. It\u2019ll take some trial and error. Once your site is working correctly, we can continue.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Configuring WordPress for Redis really is that easy! But it doesn\u2019t tell us whether it\u2019s doing us any good. We want to know: Is Redis doing its job, and making an impact on speed? Let\u2019s find out!&nbsp;</span></p><h1><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Testing Redis</span></h1><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">To know whether Redis is making a positive impact on your site, we\u2019ll need to do some load testing. For that we used <a href=\"https://loadimpact.com\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">LoadImpact.com</a>. Their free account will allow you to use up to 50 Virtual Users for 12 minutes at a time to load test your site. We configured a test for 50 Virtual Users (VU) for 3 minutes using the \u201cStress\u201d ramp-up setting as shown below:</span></p><p><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-LoadImpact.jpg\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSI4MzkiIGhlaWdodD0iNDk5IiB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgODM5IDQ5OSI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEwMCUiIGhlaWdodD0iMTAwJSIgZmlsbD0iI2NmZDRkYiIvPjwvc3ZnPg==\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-20184\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-LoadImpact.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"839\" height=\"499\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-LoadImpact.jpg.webp 839w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-LoadImpact-300x178.jpg.webp 300w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-LoadImpact-768x457.jpg.webp 768w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 839px) 100vw, 839px\"></a></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Both tests were run with W3 Total Cache installed. The \u201cDisk Caching\u201d test was done with W3 Total Cache configured for \u201cDisk\u201d or \u201cDisk: Enhanced\u201d. The \u201cRedis Caching\u201d test was done with Redis configured as previously mentioned. You can see the results in the chart below. Disk caching is Blue, while Redis caching is Red, of course.</span></p><p><a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Results.jpg\"><img data-lazyloaded=\"1\" src=\"data:image/svg+xml;base64,PHN2ZyB4bWxucz0iaHR0cDovL3d3dy53My5vcmcvMjAwMC9zdmciIHdpZHRoPSI2MzEiIGhlaWdodD0iMzczIiB2aWV3Qm94PSIwIDAgNjMxIDM3MyI+PHJlY3Qgd2lkdGg9IjEwMCUiIGhlaWdodD0iMTAwJSIgZmlsbD0iI2NmZDRkYiIvPjwvc3ZnPg==\" loading=\"lazy\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-20186\" data-src=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Results.jpg.webp\" alt=\"\" width=\"631\" height=\"373\" data-srcset=\"https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Results.jpg.webp 631w, https://lowendbox.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/Redis-Results-300x177.jpg.webp 300w\" data-sizes=\"(max-width: 631px) 100vw, 631px\"></a></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">With Disk caching enabled, our WordPress site served 27 requests per second with an average response time of 22ms. For a single core VPS with 512mb RAM, this fine.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When we reconfigured the site to use Redis, there was a very nice improvement. The server was able to serve 35 requests per second, with a slightly higher average response of 34ms. The higher response time is likely due to the server being busy handling so many more requests. Still, 34ms is quite good and completely acceptable.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">On the other hand, 35 requests per second vs 27 is VERY good. It\u2019s a 30% increase in performance, and all we had to do was install and configure Redis!&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">While we\u2019ve covered the general installation and utilization of Redis, we\u2019ve only really scratched the surface. Redis can be configured in countless different ways. Tuning for higher performance is possible, and fine tuning it for your specific requirements may yield even better results. You can learn more about Redis in the official Redis documentation: </span><a href=\"https://redis.io/documentation\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">https://redis.io/documentation</span></a></p><h1>Are we done?</h1><p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Not quite! There\u2019s still more performance to be had. In the next installment of this series, we\u2019re going to make even more use of caching by replacing Apache with a caching web server called Nginx (pronounced \u201cEngine-X\u201d). Click Here for <a href=\"https://lowendbox.com/blog/centos-7-lamp-server-tutorial-part-6-moving-to-nginx/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Part 6: Moving to NGINX</a></span></p><p class=\"dpsp-share-text\"></p><div id=\"dpsp-content-bottom\" class=\"dpsp-content-wrapper dpsp-shape-rounded dpsp-column-auto dpsp-has-spacing dpsp-no-labels dpsp-show-on-mobile dpsp-button-style-1 dpsp-has-icon-background dpsp-has-button-background dpsp-show-total-share-count dpsp-show-total-share-count-after\"><ul class=\"dpsp-networks-btns-wrapper dpsp-networks-btns-content dpsp-has-button-icon-animation\"><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://www.facebook.com/sharer/sharer.php?u=https%3A%2F%2Flowendbox.com%2Fblog%2Fcentos-7-lamp-server-tutorial-part-5-speeding-up-wordpress-with-redis%2F&amp;t=CentOS%207%20LAMP%20Server%20Tutorial%20Part%205%3A%20Speeding%20up%20WordPress%20with%20Redis\" class=\"dpsp-network-btn dpsp-facebook dpsp-no-label dpsp-first\" title=\"Share on Facebook\"><span class=\"dpsp-network-icon\"></span><span class=\"dpsp-network-labe